! Components

* ''Widget'' (`widgets/cascade-palette-widget.js`) ‚Äî implements the palette: stage stack, keyboard router, result rendering, action invocation.
* ''Startup module'' (`widgets/cascade-palette-startup.js`) ‚Äî mounts the widget into `document.body` at boot via `<$cascade-palette/>`. Independent of any page template tag so the palette works in any UI mode (default wiki, appify, custom themes).
* ''Hotkey binding'' (`config/shortcut-binding.tid` + `config/shortcut-key.tid`) ‚Äî standard TW keyboard shortcut machinery. Press the configured key (default Ctrl-Space) and TW dispatches the `rimir-cascade-palette-open` message that the widget catches via `$tw.rootWidget`.

! Stage stack

The palette is a stack of stages, growing on Right-arrow / Space / Enter-on-drill, shrinking on Esc / ArrowLeft. Stage shapes:

;`kind: "root"`
:The initial stage. Items come from tiddlers tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry`, sorted by `ca-order` then `ca-name`.
;`kind: "tree"`
:A tree-stage from a view's structure layer. Pushed when the user Right-arrows into a container (tree node with children). The parent path is carried in `parentPath`; child rows come from the originating layer's `ca-layer-children` filter (or the view's `ca-view-children` for implicit-layer views).
;`kind: "filter"`
:A stage scoped by a filter expression. Pushed when the user drills from a `ca-kind: drill` entry or action. Items are dynamic ‚Äî tiddler titles (or bare strings) returned by `ca-next-scope`.
;`kind: "actions"`
:An action-menu stage. Pushed when the user Right-arrows on a typed leaf (via `ca-layer-row-entity-type`), Space's on any typed row (leaf or container), or drills on a dynamic entity item in a filter stage. Items are tiddlers tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action` whose `ca-entity-type` matches the resolved type (plus globals tagged `ca-entity-type: *`), further narrowed by each action's optional `ca-action-when` applicability filter.
;`kind: "confirm"`
:A two-row Confirm / Cancel stage pushed when a leaf action carries `ca-confirm: yes`, or on Delete-on-row for destructive list operations. The consequence text shows inline as the Confirm row's hint AND in the detail drawer banner.

The keyboard router does one of:

* ''Type'' ‚Üí update current stage's `query`, recompute items.
* ''Up/Down'' ‚Üí move `selectedIndex`.
* ''Right-arrow'' ‚Üí drill from the selected item (push new stage). On typed leaves, pushes the action-menu stage.
* ''Space'' ‚Üí on toggle/text/number/date kinds, kind-specific edit; on any other row with a non-empty entity type, pushes the action-menu stage (works for containers too).
* ''Enter'' ‚Üí fire the selected item's default behaviour (leaf action OR push if drill).
* ''Esc'' ‚Üí pop one stage. From input at root depth, closes the palette; from menu at root depth, refocuses input.
* ''Shift-Esc'' ‚Üí close the palette from any focus and any depth in one keystroke. Freezes the current stack to `$:/temp/rimir/cascade-palette/saved-stack` so the next open resumes here.

! Axes ‚Äî per-layer grouping chains

A structure-layer can declare a chain of ''axes'' that group the layer's source set by a derived key ‚Äî year, month, day, status, prefix, or any tiddler-to-string mapping you can write as a filter. Each axis runs at one tree depth: first axis at root, second under each first-axis bucket, and so on. Axes ''compose with the layer's recursive `children` filter'': past the chain, the children filter takes over with the source narrowed to whatever leaf bucket the user drilled into. The two concepts are orthogonal halves of the same descent ‚Äî axes form the top, children forms the bottom.

!! The descent at a glance

```
depth:    0       1       2       3            4        5       ‚Ä¶
        ‚îå‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îê  ‚îå‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îê
data:   ‚îÇ  AXIS CHAIN (buckets)   ‚îÇ  ‚îÇ  RECURSIVE TREE         ‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ  parentPath[i] = key    ‚îÇ  ‚îÇ  parentPath[i] = tiddler‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ  source = layer.roots,  ‚îÇ  ‚îÇ  filter = layer.children‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ  narrowed by axis-keys  ‚îÇ  ‚îÇ  currentTiddler = parent‚îÇ
        ‚îÇ  matching parentPath    ‚îÇ  ‚îÇ                         ‚îÇ
        ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò
                       ‚Üë                ‚Üë
                    transition: parentPath.length === chain.length
```

`parentPath` (the array carried on every tree-stage) holds bucket keys for indices `0..chain.length - 1` and real tiddler titles for indices `chain.length..`. The reader doesn't need a type check: depth alone tells the engine which interpretation applies.

!! Three useful configurations of a single layer

|!Axes |!Children |!Behaviour |
|empty |empty |Flat list. `roots` is the source, every row is a leaf. (Today's ''All tiddlers''.) |
|empty |set |Pure recursive tree ‚Äî same `children` filter at every depth, source narrowed by `<currentTiddler>` rebinding. (Today's ''By parent'', ''By namespace''.) Axes never engage. |
|set |empty |Pure grouping. Buckets all the way down; at the deepest axis, the leaves are tiddlers from the narrowed source ‚Äî no further descent. (Shipped ''By date''.) |
|set |set |Bucket the source first, then descend each leaf-bucket tiddler via `children` as today. E.g. ''By parent, sliced by year'' ‚Äî TOC tiddlers grouped by year, each TOC then expanding its tag-subtree. |

!! Transition mechanics

At the exact moment `parentPath.length === chain.length` (axes consumed but no tiddler drilled yet), the engine calls `cp-axes.sourceAfterAxes` to emit `layer.roots` narrowed by every parent bucket key. Each result row is a real tiddler ‚Äî and runs through the same row-builder as every other tiddler row in the engine: `_isLeafInLayer` decides drill vs. leaf by asking ''"does `layer.children` return anything under this tiddler?"'' (empty children ‚Üí always leaf; non-empty ‚Üí `_treeContainer = true`).

That single test is the only place axes and children indirectly meet. After it, drilling appends the picked tiddler title to `parentPath`, depth becomes `chain.length + 1`, and the descent is in standard recursive mode ‚Äî `layer.children` evaluates with `<currentTiddler> = parentPath[last]` exactly like today's tree views.

!! Two practical caveats

# ''`layer.roots` is doing double duty.'' It's both the ''universe to bucket'' (when the axis chain is evaluating) AND the ''forest roots'' at the transition. If you write `ca-layer-roots: [!is[system]]`, every non-system tiddler is bucketable AND every non-system tiddler is a recursive root candidate. If you write `ca-layer-roots: [tag[TOC]]`, only TOC-tagged tiddlers participate in either phase. Same filter, two consumers.
# ''Cross-bucket children.'' Past the transition, `layer.children` runs with `<currentTiddler>` = the parent ''tiddler'', not the bucket path. A 2025-tagged child of a 2026 TOC tiddler will appear in the 2026 subtree ‚Äî the date stops following you down. That's almost always what you want for tag-trees. If you need date-coherent descent, intersect a date predicate into `ca-layer-children`.

!! Axis schema (tag `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis`)

|!Field |!Purpose |
|`ca-axis-name` |Pill label / picker label |
|`ca-axis-hint` |Detail-drawer help text |
|`ca-axis-key` |Filter (`<currentTiddler>` = row tiddler) returning the bucket key |
|`ca-axis-label` |Optional pretty-label filter (`<currentTiddler>` = bucket key) |
|`ca-axis-sort` |`first-seen` (default) / `asc` / `desc` / `enum` |
|`ca-axis-sort-keys` |Space-separated key order; used by `enum` sort |
|`ca-axis-empty-label` |Bucket label when the key resolves to empty (default `‚Äî`) |
|`ca-axis-icon` |Optional bucket glyph |

Parametric axes (e.g. shipped `by-field`) reference `<axis-param-X>` variables in their key/label filters; per-pill params are stored alongside the axis title in the session state and bound at evaluation time as `<<axis-param-X>>` widget variables.

!! Pill UX

The Structure pill-row (`viewconfig` strip) renders each axis in the active chain as a yellow ''by'' / ''‚Üí'' pill in that layer's mini-row, plus a dashed ''+'' pill at the end. In expanded mode (Tab to the strip, Enter to expand):

* ''Backspace / Delete'' on a focused axis pill removes it from the chain.
* ''Shift-‚Üê / Shift-‚Üí'' reorders it within the chain.
* ''Enter'' on a chain pill swaps it via the axis picker.
* ''Enter / Space'' on the ''+'' pill appends a new axis.

The picker is itself a cascade stage ‚Äî a (`_freezeItems`) filter-stage listing every tiddler tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis`. On commit, `cp-axes.writeChainState` persists the new chain to `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/layer-axes/<layer-slug>` and `popStage` bounces focus back to the strip. Cancel (Esc) leaves state untouched.

!! State precedence

* Session override in `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/layer-axes/<slug>` wins over the layer's declared `ca-layer-axes`.
* Resetting (delete the state tiddler) reverts to the declared default.
* `$:/state/...` survives reload but is NOT filesystem-synced ‚Äî same pattern as `cp-leader` state.

Schema in the state tiddler: JSON `{ "axes": [ { "title": "...", "params": {‚Ä¶} }, ... ] }`. Bare strings are accepted shorthand for un-parameterised axes in either the declared default OR the state ‚Äî `parseChainSpec` handles both shapes.

!! Performance

Axis `keyFn` results are memoised per `(axisTitle + paramsHash) √ó tiddlerTitle`, invalidated on `wiki.getChangeCount()`. First touch of the cache fills it; subsequent re-renders cost O(rows visited at the current depth), not O(source). For a 3-axis chain over a 2500-tiddler source: ~150ms cold first-render, then near-zero on subsequent keystrokes.

The `groupBy` / `sortGroups` primitive is loaded from `$:/plugins/rimir/mindmap/lib/grouped-tree.js` when the mindmap plugin is installed (soft-dep); a tiny inline fallback covers the case where mindmap isn't around ‚Äî same algorithm, no feature degradation.

! Session stack persistence

`close()` paths split into two camps: ''preserve'' (Shift-Esc, action-fire close ‚Äî including the default close-on-fire via `afterAction`) write the current stack to `$:/temp/rimir/cascade-palette/saved-stack`, and ''reset'' (plain Esc at root, backdrop click, `popStage` past root) clear it. `openPalette()` reads that tiddler on each open; if present, the stack is restored (with `items`/`results` left empty for `recomputeStage` to repopulate); else a fresh root is built. `confirm` and `actions` stages are dropped on serialize ‚Äî they reference closure-captured strings or a parent-picked tiddler that may be gone ‚Äî so the saved chain truncates at the first such stage. `openPaletteAtEntry` (and the `OPEN_ENTRY_MESSAGE` handler) pass `{ fresh: true }` to skip restore, since the caller is explicitly pointing at one entry. Filters / visibilities / reaches / fields persist independently across open/close ‚Äî this layers stack-resume on top.

! Variable substitution

Filter and action wikitext receives a synthetic widget context that exposes:

* `<<query>>` ‚Äî current input
* `<<picked>>` ‚Äî the item picked in the current stage (for actions; empty during `ca-next-scope` evaluation)
* `<<parent-picked>>` ‚Äî the item picked in the parent stage
* `<<stage-N-picked>>` ‚Äî the item picked at stage index N (root = 0)

The widget assembles these via `buildStageVariables()` walking the stack.

! Navigator routing

The widget mounts in `document.body` via the startup module, so it lives OUTSIDE the page template's main widget subtree. Without intervention, actions invoked from the palette (e.g. `<$action-navigate>`, `tm-edit-tiddler`) would bubble up through the widget's only parent (`$tw.rootWidget`) and stop ‚Äî never reaching the navigator widget that lives inside the page tree.

The fix lives in `invokeViaNavigator()`: at action-fire time the widget searches `$tw.pageWidgetNode`'s subtree for the navigator (a `<$navigator>` widget) and constructs the action widget tree with the navigator as its parent. Events then bubble naturally into the navigator's handlers.

Falls back to `$tw.rootWidget` if no navigator is found, so messages with global root-level handlers (`tm-save-wiki`, custom messages) still work even without a navigator.

! Action discovery

At every keystroke / stage push, the widget runs cheap filter queries to populate items:

* Entries: `[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry]]`
* Actions for type T: `[all[shadows+tiddlers]tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action]]` filtered to `ca-entity-type === T` ‚ãÉ `ca-entity-type === "*"`

There is no caching ‚Äî adding/removing action tiddlers takes effect immediately (the next palette open or stage push picks them up). Performance is fine for catalogues of a few hundred tiddlers; if your catalogue grows much larger consider adding a result cache keyed on `wiki.getChangeCount()`.

